EmergencyResponce_Descr:
EMERGENCY RESPONSE CRITIQUE&lt;br&gt;
During the incident the overall response by the internal intervention
team was adequate. Sprinklers were activated instantaneously. The foam
system was activated 2 minutes after the event and after blocking the
sprinkler system. The pool fire was fed on a continuous basis by back
flow of cumene. The external fire brigade was warned at 14.02.&lt;br&gt;
Arrival external fire brigade at 14.24. &lt;br&gt;
The intervention team and the external fire brigade managed to separate an area of 10 by 10m by installing a water curtain. &lt;br&gt;
The overflow of the bund created a supplementary problem. The fire was
spread over a larger area which enabled more damage to electrical cable
trenches.&amp;nbsp; Additionally minor soil contamination was introduced by the
overflow. &lt;br&gt;
The overflow was&amp;nbsp; a direct consequence of&amp;nbsp; a loss of the power supply
of sump pumps and the absence of an additional emergency overflow&lt;br&gt;
The duration of the event was prolonged by the lack of effective means
to stop the back flow of cumene on short notice. At 15.20 the back flow
was stopped, leading to total control of the situation at 15.25.&lt;br&gt;
During the whole event foam and water supply proved to be sufficient at al times.&lt;br&gt;
The emergency response team acted conform internal procedure, except
for the external communications to neighbouring companies and one local
authority, that had only been informed indirectly.&lt;br&gt;
The first official information in writing was provided rather late (2hr after start event).&lt;br&gt;
At a later stage (approx 18.00) the competent authorities were de-briefed and informed adequately.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
